                <h2>Whether Your Appeal Succeeds Depends on Identifying the Right Reason</h2>
<p>Anyone involved in overseas advertising knows that Google Ads account suspension is frustrating. Many clients' first reaction is to quickly fill out the appeal form, attaching numerous screenshots and explanations,恨不得把所有能想到的材料都附上去. But based on dozens of account appeal cases we've handled, this "blanket approach" is extremely inefficient—disorganized materials can actually make it harder for reviewers to assess the situation.</p>
<p><strong>The conclusion is clear: the key to successful appeals is not the volume of materials, but precisely identifying the suspension reason and providing targeted evidence.</strong> Google's review system has specific criteria for each violation type. Appeal materials only work when they hit these criteria directly.</p>
<h2>Common Suspension Reasons and Corresponding Appeal Strategies</h2>
<p>From operational experience, Google Ads account suspensions fall into several main categories, each requiring completely different material preparation approaches:</p>
<h3>1. Malware or Phishing Related</h3>
<p>This is the most common issue for utility app and gaming teams going overseas. If your landing page is flagged for containing malicious download links or redirecting to third-party malicious sites—even if you weren't aware—your account will be suspended.</p>
<p><strong>Key Materials to Prepare:</strong><br />
- Hosting platform access records proving control over the landing page<br />
- Current page status from Google Safe Browsing diagnostic tools<br />
- Before/after screenshots if already fixed<br />
- Detailed remediation notes specifying which code or links were modified</p>
<h3>2. Trademark Infringement or Misrepresentation</h3>
<p>E-commerce sellers sometimes get suspended for using competitor brand names in ad copy or having product descriptions that don't match actual items. These appeals typically take longer to resolve.</p>
<p><strong>Key Materials to Prepare:</strong><br />
- Brand authorization documents or proprietary trademark registrations<br />
- Comparison of product photos vs. landing page descriptions<br />
- Historical advertising performance reports showing long-term normal operation<br />
- A sincere statement acknowledging possible misrepresentation and committing to corrections</p>
<h3>3. Circumvention Behavior</h3>
<p>If Google detects hidden redirects, arbitrage structures, or attempts to circumvent policy review in your ads, the account enters permanent suspension status. These appeals are the most difficult. <strong>We recommend evaluating whether it's worth the effort before investing time in appeals</strong>, as accounts with good historical records have a better chance of reinstatement.</p>
<p><strong>Key Materials to Prepare:</strong><br />
- Technical website architecture explanation demonstrating no intentional circumvention<br />
- Recent advertising performance reports proving normal投放行为<br />
- Third-party security audit reports as supporting evidence</p>
<h2>Three Practical Tips for Appeal Material Preparation</h2>
<h3>Tip 1: Check the Official Email First, Then the Policy Center</h3>
<p>When an account is suspended, Google sends an email with subject "Account Suspended." This email typically contains a violation code or type description. Once you find this code, search the Google Ads Policy Center for the corresponding policy and compare it word-by-word with your actual operations. <strong>Many clients skip this step and write appeals based on assumptions, resulting in completely off-topic submissions.</strong></p>
<h3>Tip 2: Keep Materials Under 3 Pages in PDF Format</h3>
<p>Reviewers handle numerous cases daily. Lengthy materials dilute the key points instead of emphasizing them. Our template typically includes:<br />
- Page 1: Self-assessment of violation type + basic account information<br />
- Page 2: Evidence materials (screenshots, documents, reports)<br />
- Page 3: Remediation measures and commitments</p>
<p>Appeals exceeding three pages may result in reviewers making decisions after only reading the first page.</p>
<h3>Tip 3: Avoid Repeated Appeals on the Same Issue</h3>
<p>Many clients resubmit identical materials within 48 hours after rejection. This gets flagged as "harassment behavior" by the system, actually lowering subsequent appeal weight. <strong>The correct approach: analyze rejection reasons, adjust materials, and wait 5-7 business days before resubmitting.</strong></p>
<h2>A Final Reminder</h2>
<p>Account appeals have no guaranteed success, especially for fraud or malicious behavior suspensions. However, if you can quickly identify the issue type and prepare logically clear supporting materials, your success rate will be significantly higher than blind submissions. In handling these cases, we found that <strong>approximately 70% of account suspensions actually stem from landing page or ad copy details rather than malicious violations</strong>—these cases typically can be reinstated after providing sufficient remediation evidence.</p>
<p>If you're struggling with an account appeal, we recommend first clarifying the suspension reason before taking action. Don't let emotions drive your appeal strategy.</p>
